<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n13102c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n13" href="#n13102c">N13 (VI.D.3)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n13all.htm#n13102c"> 102(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> disease of lingua</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The Oriental philologist of Oxford, Max Muller, in attempting to explain how myths arose (according to his theory) from a <mark>disease of language</mark>, thinks that during the transition period of which he speaks there would be many words &ldquo;understood perhaps by the grandfather, familiar to the father, but strange to the son, and misunderstood by the grandson.&rdquo; This is exactly what is taking place over half Ireland at this very moment, and it is what has always been at work amongst a people whose language and literature go back with certainty for nearly 1,500 years. <small> Douglas Hyde, <a name="SEGL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SEGL"><cite title="source">The Story of Early Gaelic Literature</cite></a> (1920) 29</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05041c" href="c5all.htm#c05041c">VI.C.05:041(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
